    "summary": "The Ishtar Gate (c. 575 BC) was the eighth gate of the inner city of Babylon, commissioned by Nebuchadnezzar II and dedicated to the goddess Ishtar. It was the most magnificent entrance to the ancient city — a towering double gate of deep blue glazed bricks decorated with alternating rows of relief-molded dragons (mushhushshu, symbols of the god Marduk) and bulls (symbols of the storm god Adad), set at the start of the Processional Way that led through the city to the Esagila temple complex.\n\nThe gate stood approximately 14 meters high (with a possible second tower above) and was flanked by walls stretching for over 180 meters on each side. The vivid blue color was achieved through lapis lazuli-colored glaze — at once a display of enormous wealth (lapis lazuli was precious) and a stunning visual statement. The Processional Way itself was paved with stone imported from distant quarries and lined with lions in glazed brick. Excavated by German archaeologist Robert Koldewey between 1899 and 1917, most of the gate was transported to Berlin where a reconstructed version (partially original fragments, partially modern reconstruction) stands in the Pergamon Museum — one of the most impressive ancient objects in any museum.",
